instructions = 'This week\'s contest answer is a famous character of literature and film.'
explanation = '<MA>HAL 9000</MA><TEXT>The number in parentheses following each theme clue is the decimal equivalent of the binary number formed by the Os and Is (read as zeroes and ones) in the answer, read from left-to-right (i.e. big-endian). The only other Os and Is are found on the NW-SE diagonal, which, if also read as a big-endian binary number, represent 2001. The most famous character from Arthur C. Clarke\'s or Stanley Kubrick\'s "2001: A Space Odyssey" is HAL 9000. Appropriately, HAL is a computer.<br/><br/>Note that there was a small but significant error in the original version of this puzzle, which I have since corrected. An extraneous O was allowed to sneak into the fill in the NW corner, although the only Is and Os that were meant to be in the grid were the ones on the main diagonal and in the long theme answers.</TEXT>'
